[start section id="20112"]

A 70-year-old woman with a history of a recent stroke, hypertension, diabetes, presenting for evaluation of a diagnosis of colon cancer.
IMPRESSION
#1 Colon cancer
#2 Scattered polyps throughout the ascending transverse and descending colon--histopathology unknown
#3 Large multi-cm polyp in the sigmoid colon--mass in the proximal colon
#4 Recent CVA
It appears that the adenocarcinoma is in the proximal colon.  The additional lesions are of unclear clinical significance.  It would be important to further delineate for perioperative planning.  In addition, she does have multiple medical comorbidities that does put her at a higher risk, particularly with her recent CVA for any surgical procedure.
RECOMMENDATIONS
1. We will perform a colonoscopy with the request that the endoscopist treat other benign polyps and biopsy any suspicious lesions for perioperative planning: hemicolectomy versus total colectomy. She was instructed to hold her diabetic medications while fasting.
2. We will request the outside CT of her abdomen and pelvis to be reviewed here.
3. We will request outside information be sent over including if any additional studies such as CT of her head and carotid ultrasounds were performed.
4. We will refer her to our colleagues in Cardiology for a perioperative assessment and clearance.
5. We will refer her to Nicotine cessation.
6. She will be evaluated by surgeons after initial work-up is complete.
7. We will perform routine labs including chest x-ray, EKG.
8. Have her return after her initial studies including her colonoscopy have been completed.
The above plan was discussed with Dr. Kendall Miller and Rena Lundy who were in agreement.
ADVANCE DIRECTIVES
Advance directive or living will: No, not interested in additional information.

[end section id="20112"]

