[start section id="20103"]

Mrs. Villalobos is a 70-year-old woman with a history of a recent stroke, type-2 diabetes, hypertension, presenting for the below concerns:
#1 Colon cancer
#2 History of iron-deficiency anemia
Over the summer, Mrs. Villalobos had noted progressive fatigue.  She is noted to have iron-deficiency anemia.  Subsequently, she underwent an upper endoscopy that showed patchy antral erythema consistent with gastritis but was otherwise unremarkable.  Gastric biopsies were negative including for H. pylori.  Small-bowel biopsies were also negative as well.  Underwent a colonoscopy at the same time, and per the report, it stated that there was a tumor cecal base, which cannot be intubated secondary to stricturing, and the mass lesion ascended into the proximal ascending colon.  When they withdrew the endoscope there were three large flat polyps spaced 10 to 15-cm apart.  That was more proximal to an unknown location based on the wording in the endoscopy report.  The endoscopist also noted small polyps in the ascending, transverse, and descending colon.  In the sigmoid colon there was a large round multi-cm polyp that was suspicious for advanced adenoma or possible early malignancy, and one fold distal to this there was a small round polyp that was approximately 1-cm in diameter.  This was at roughly 25 cm from the anal verge.  This area was tattooed.  Four diminutive polyps were noted in the sigmoid.  Those were removed with snare polypectomy.  Pathology showed invasive moderately differentiated adenocarcinoma from the colonic mass and that the sigmoid polyps were hyperplastic.  She subsequently had a CT-scan that showed a long-segment lesion involving the cecum with abnormal thickening of the colonic walls and narrowing of the lumen measuring of at least 8-cm.  The liver and spleen were negative.  No evidence of metastases were noted.
Since then she has been feeling well.  Does have some constipation with her iron supplementations but denies nausea, vomiting, abdominal distention, or worsening constipation, as she does have bowel movements once every several days.  In June she did have a stroke, which left her with increasing gait difficulties and probable cranial nerve XII palsy.  However, she has still been able to get around at-home where she lives with her husband without too much difficulty as long as she is using a four-pronged cane.

[end section id="20103"]

